{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"88f04348-a414-4e46-a359-61c80451389a","content":"TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform natively, so you filter with `--treenode-filter` (not `--filter`):\n\n```bash\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/**/SmsNotificationTests/**\"\n```\n\nThis matches the `SmsNotificationTests` class at any depth in the test tree and includes all test methods within it. It will run `SendSms_HealthCheck` and `SendSms_ValidPhone_Succeeds`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"029faaa2-5dad-45e1-9afe-6e99f8cf20e4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"This is a TUnit project. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform (MTP) natively. For MTP-based runners, the filter syntax is different from VSTest.\n\nFor TUnit with MTP, the class filter would use `--treenode-filter`:\n\n```\ndotnet test --treenode-filter \"/*/*/SmsNotificationTests\"\n```\n\nWait, let me think about TUnit's filter syntax. TUnit uses Microsoft.Testing.Platform, which uses `--treenode-filter` for filtering. The tree node filter format for TUnit is typically:\n\n```\n/Namespace/ClassName/MethodName\n```\n\n\nSo to filter by class name `SmsNotificationTests`, I need to account for the wildcard patterns that MTP supports. The exact syntax depends on how TUnit structures its test tree nodes, but something like using wildcards to match the class name at the appropriate level should work. I'm trying to pin down the precise format—whether it's a simple glob pattern or if TUnit has specific conventions for class-level filtering. Finalizing the command syntax...\n\nThe treenode filter pattern for TUnit uses the MTP format with assembly, namespace, class, and test method levels, so filtering by the `SmsNotificationTests` class would use the glob pattern with wildcards to match any depth and capture all test methods within that class.","outputTokens":819,"requestId":"4808:5F204:5C4F9B7:6412968:69FBEA40"},"id":"9427ac3b-a2cc-43b4-a06e-ead9123a9179","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:26:41.371Z","par